Preheat your #oven{} to 240°C/220°C fan/gas mark 9.

Remove the @butter{20%g} from your fridge and leave to one side to soften.

Chop the @sweet potato{1} into 1cm chunks (no need to peel) and pop them onto a
large #baking tray{}.

Drizzle with @oil{} and @salt{}, season with @pepper{}, then toss to coat. Spread
out in a single layer.

> TIP: Use two baking trays if necessary.

When the oven is hot, roast on the top shelf until golden, ~{16-18%mins}. Turn
halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125}. Peel and grate the
@garlic clove{3}(2 halves grated and 1 clove left whole) (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium heat.

Once hot, add the @rogan josh curry paste{50%g}, half the garlic and half the
@chilli flakes{1} (add less if you'd prefer things milder). Stir-fry for
~{1%min}.

Stir in the tomatoes and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Cook, stirring
occasionally, until the tomatoes start to soften, ~{2-3%mins}.

While the tomatoes cook, drain and rinse the @chickpeas{1%400g can} in a
#sieve{}.

Pour the @tomato passata{1%400ml}, chickpeas, @vegetable stock paste{10%g} and
@water{100%ml} into the pan.

Stir and bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened,
~{4-5%mins}.

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine the @butter{} and remaining garlic. Season
with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Put the @plain naan{2} onto a #baking tray{}. Spread the garlic butter over them
and pop them into the oven to warm through, ~{3-4%mins}.

Once the sweet potato is ready, remove from the oven and stir it through the
curry.

Stir in the @mango chutney{40%g}, then taste and season with more @salt{} and
@pepper{} if needed.

Spoon the sweet potato curry into your #bowls{}.

Sprinkle over the @toasted flaked almonds{15%g} and remaining chilli flakes (add
less if you'd prefer things milder).

Halve the garlic naans and serve them alongside for dipping and scooping. Enjoy!